>2021-03-17T10:23:10</eventDateTime><agentType>human</agentType><agent>James Truitt (jtruitt1@swarthmore.edu)</agent><eventDescription>Republish: User canceled edit without making changes</eventDescription></maintenanceEvent><maintenanceEvent><eventType>revised</eventType><eventDateTime standardDateTime="2021-04-05T14:23:10">2021-04-05T14:23:10</eventDateTime><agentType>human</agentType><agent>James Truitt (jtruitt1@swarthmore.edu)</agent><eventDescription>User published constellation</eventDescription></maintenanceEvent></maintenanceHistory><sources><source><sourceEntry>First Record Book of Births and Deaths of Members of Evesham Monthly Meeting, via Ancestry.com search, January 20, 2021</sourceEntry><descriptiveNote><p>p. 27. John Hunt, born the 5th day of 6th Month, 1740; son of Robert Hunt, born the 21st of 2nd Month 1709, and Abigail his wife.</p></descriptiveNote></source><source xlink:href="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/70973480" xlink:type="simple" /><source xlink:href="http://viaf.org/viaf/56005394" xlink:type="simple" /><source><sourceEntry>Evesham Monthly Meeting First Book of Marriages, via Ancestry.com search, January 20, 2021</sourceEntry><descriptiveNote><p>p. 22. John Hunt, son of Robert Hunt, and Esther Warrington, daughter of Henry Warrington, were married on the Seventeenth Day of ye 3d month 1763</p></descriptiveNote></source><source><sourceEntry>Hunt, John, “Our Beloved Friend” : The Journals of John Hunt, 1770-1824, 2018</sourceEntry><descriptiveNote><p>p. vi-vii. The oldest son of Robert and Abigail Hunt of Haddonfield Monthly Meeting, John was born in August of 1740.... He and Esther Warrington, daughter of Henry and Elizabeth (Bishop) Warrington, were married on March 17, 1763, under the care of Evesham Monthly Meeting.... By 1766, John was appointed as delegate to Salem Quarterly Meeting.... John Hunt's father, Robert, was a first cousin to John Woolman (1720-1772), journalist and minister. Esther Hunt's nephew, Abraham Warrington, married Rachel Evans, daughter of John Hunt's friend and fellow minister, Joshua Evans.</p></descriptiveNote></source></sources></control><cpfDescription><identity><entityType>person</entityType><nameEntry><part>Hunt, John, 1740-1824</part></nameEntry><entityId>https://viaf.org/viaf/48963351</entityId><entityId>https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no2005064399</entityId><entityId>https://id.loc.gov/authorities/no2005064399</entityId><entityId>https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q6240437</entityId><entityId>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/137891527</entityId><entityId>https://viaf.org/viaf/56005394</entityId><entityId>https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n2004072579</entityId><entityId>https://id.loc.gov/authorities/n2004072579</entityId><entityId>http://n2t.net/ark:/99166/http://n2t.net/ark:/99166/w6n9820p</entityId></identity><description><existDates><dateRange><fromDate standardDate="1740-08-05" localType="Birth">1740-08-05</fromDate><toDate standardDate="1824-09-21" localType="Birth">1824-09-21</toDate></dateRange></existDates><languageUsed><language languageCode="eng">English</language><script scriptCode="Latn">Latin</script></languageUsed><localDescriptions><localDescription localType="gender"><term>Male</term></localDescription><localDescription localType="associatedSubject"><term>Society of Friends</term></localDescription><localDescription localType="associatedSubject"><term>Quakers</term></localDescription><localDescription localType="associatedSubject"><term>Lay ministry--Society of Friends</term></localDescription></localDescriptions><place><placeEntry>New Jersey</placeEntry></place><occupations><occupation><term>Quakers</term></occupation><occupation><term>Farmers--New Jersey</term></occupation><occupation><term>Clergy</term></occupation></occupations><biogHist><biogHist><p xmlns="urn:isbn:1-931666-33-4">John Hunt was born in 1740, the son of Robert and Abigail (Wood) Hunt of New Jersey. His father was a first cousin to the John Woolman (1720-1772). In 1763, John Hunt married Esther Warrington in the Chester meeting house, under the supervision of Evesham Monthly Meeting. He was a Quaker minister for more than 50 years and died in 1824. His memorial, published in 1841, highlighted his public testimony concerning pride and superfluity, and stated that he was particularly concerned with temperance.</p>
